{
  "text": "As a cornerstone of modern biomedical research, the use of mouse models has dominated scientific literature [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The prevailing assumption-that molecular results from current mouse models developed to mimic human diseases translate directly to human conditions-is challenged by our study. Because virtually every drug and drug candidate functions at the molecular level, one practical approach forward is to raise the bar by requiring molecular detail in the animal model studies indicating whether the model mimics or fails to mimic the molecular behavior of key genes, key pathways, or the genome-wide level thought to be important for the relevant human disease.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "23788054",
    "[CITATION_2]": "205359417"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "23788054": {
      "title": "The FDA critical path initiative and its influence on new drug development",
      "abstract": "Societal expectations about drug safety and efficacy are rising while productivity in the pharmaceutical industry is falling. In 2004, the US Food and Drug Administration introduced the Critical Path Initiative with the intent of modernizing drug development by incorporating recent scientific advances, such as genomics and advanced imaging technologies, into the process. An important part of the initiative is the use of public-private partnerships and consortia to accomplish the needed research. This article explicates the reasoning behind the Critical Path Initiative and discusses examples of successful consortia."
    },
    "205359417": {
      "title": "The habitual, diverse and surmountable obstacles to human immunology research",
      "abstract": "The need to translate basic research in the field of human immunology may be much more urgent, and the rewards potentially much greater, than is often acknowledged. Yet a commonly perceived coercion to undertake translational research may be unhelpful. Instead, we propose clear incentives for integrating key skill sets, together with achievable cultural adjustments in research and medicine that span training, recruitment and promotion."
    }
  }
}